Under the Fixing Long-Term Care Act, 2021 (S.O. 2021, c. 39, Sched. 1), there are two routes by which a long-term care home licence can be suspended or revoked: an order by the Director under section 159, and a suspension by the Minister under section 161.

Section 159 — Director's suspension or revocation. Under section 159(1), the Director may make an order suspending or revoking a licence. Section 159(2) sets out the grounds; a licence may be suspended or revoked if:
(a) the licensee has not complied with a requirement under this Act;
(b) any person has made a false statement in the application for the licence, or the licensee (or any person acting on the licensee's behalf) has made a false statement in any report, document or other information required to be furnished under this Act or any other legislation in relation to the long-term care home;
(c) the conduct of the licensee, a person with a controlling interest in the licensee, or (where the licensee is a corporation) its officers and directors, affords reasonable grounds to believe that the home will not be operated in accordance with the law and with honesty and integrity, or will be operated in a manner prejudicial to the health, safety or welfare of its residents;
(d) the licensee is no longer eligible to be issued/hold the licence (i.e., no longer meets the eligibility requirements such as those in section 101);
(e) a person has taken over the operation of the long-term care home by exercising a security interest in accordance with section 110, and the conditions provided for in the regulations apply; or
(f) a person has gained a controlling interest in the licensee without the approval of the Director, contrary to section 112, or a condition of such an approval has been breached.

Procedural features of section 159: an order suspending a licence takes effect immediately upon the licensee being served with a copy of the order (s.159(3)), without impeding the right of appeal to the Appeal Board. Having suspended or revoked a licence, the Director may also order the home to be occupied and operated by a long-term care home supervisor (s.159(5)). A suspension does not preclude the Director from later revoking the same licence if satisfied the licensee cannot or will not properly operate the home (s.159(6)).

Section 161 — Minister's suspension. Separately, under section 161(1), if the Minister has reasonable grounds to believe that a long-term care home is being operated, or will be operated, in a manner that is prejudicial to the health, safety or welfare of its residents, the Minister may make an order suspending the licence for the home. Where the Minister makes such an order, sections 159 to 177 apply with necessary modifications, and the Lieutenant Governor in Council may appoint a supervisor on the Minister's recommendation.

There is no automatic stay of a suspension or revocation order on appeal: under section 172(2), the no-automatic-stay rule applies to orders to suspend or revoke a licence under section 159(1) and to suspend under section 161(1).
